    • Method Detail

      • getSaturationIntensity

        public int getSaturationIntensity()
        This function has nothing to do with TEC. But because the saturationIntensity value is stored in the same EEPROM slot as the TEC settings, it was convenient to piggy-back the saturation intensity feature onto the TEC feature.
        Returns:
        -1 if this spectrometer does not support the saturationIntensity feature.

      • setSaturationIntensity

        public boolean setSaturationIntensity(int saturationIntensity,
                                      java.lang.String key)
        This function has nothing to do with TEC. But because the saturationIntensity value is stored in the same EEPROM slot as the TEC settings, it was convenient to piggy-back the saturation intensity feature onto the TEC feature.
        Returns:
        true if successful, else return false if this spectrometer does not support the saturationIntensity feature.

      • setFanEnable

        public void setFanEnable(boolean enable)
                  throws java.io.IOException
        Sets the power state for the device fan. The underlying command is expected to be OP_FANON (0x0D) for the NIRs.
        Parameters:
        enable - true will power the fan, false will shut it down
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the command cannot be sent to the device.

      • getFanEnable

        public boolean getFanEnable()
        Gets the state of the device fan. As this feature is not supported by the hardware, the state will be cached in the driver. The true state will not be known until setFanEnable() is called, so if this is called first, the result will be indeterminate (null).
        Returns:
        Boolean containing true if the fan is powered on or false if it is not; can also return null when the state is not yet known.

      • setDetectorSetPointCelsius

        public void setDetectorSetPointCelsius(double point)
                                throws java.io.IOException
        Performs a write command to the TEC controller. This command is used to set the detector's TEC set point temperature. The set-point value is a signed 16-bit value that is expressed in tenths of a degree Celsius. For example to set the temperature to -5.0 C a value of -50 or 0xFFCD is sent.
        Parameters:
        point - the value to set the detectors TEC set point temperature.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - if errors occur communicating with the spectrometer.

      • getDetectorSetPointCelsius

        Returns:
        The detector's TEC set point temperature.

      • isSaveTECStateEnabled

        public boolean isSaveTECStateEnabled()
        The QE65000 allows users to save the last state of the TEC state, Fan state, and setpoint. The QE65000 will return true. All others will return false, disallowing the ability to saveTECState()
        Returns:
        true if saving the TEC state is enabled, false otherwise.

      • saveTECState

        public void saveTECState()
                  throws java.io.IOException
        The QE65000 allows users to save the last state of the TEC state, Fan state, and setpoint. Calling isSaveTECStateEnabled will return true if using a QE65000. All other spectrometers will return false, disallowing the ability to saveTECState()
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - if an error occurs while communicating with the spectrometer
